{
  "id": "integrating-polynomials",
  "title": "Integrating Polynomials",
  "order": 11,
  "estimatedMinutes": 8,
  "conceptTags": ["antiderivative", "definite_integral"],
  "published": true,
  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "ip-step-1",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Integration runs differentiation in reverse, and it splits over sums in exactly the same way. To integrate a polynomial, integrate each term on its own and add the results — the sum rule again."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int \\big(f(x) + g(x)\\big)\\,dx = \\int f(x)\\,dx + \\int g(x)\\,dx",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Each term uses the reverse power rule: add 1 to the exponent, then divide by the new exponent. So $x^2 + x$ integrates to:"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int (x^2 + x)\\,dx = \\int x^2\\,dx + \\int x\\,dx = \\frac{x^3}{3} + \\frac{x^2}{2}",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-2",
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Integrate term by term. Which is an antiderivative of $f(x) = x^2 + x$?"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "x^2 + x",
          "domain": [0, 3],
          "yDomain": [0, 12],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 2,
          "static": true
        },
        "answer": {
          "type": "multiple_choice",
          "options": [
            "$\\frac{x^3}{3} + \\frac{x^2}{2}$",
            "$x^3 + x^2$",
            "$2x + 1$",
            "$\\frac{x^3}{3} + x^2$"
          ],
          "correctIndex": 0
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — reverse the power rule on each term: $x^2 \\to \\frac{x^3}{3}$ and $x \\to \\frac{x^2}{2}$.",
        "incorrect": "Add 1 to each exponent and divide by the new exponent, term by term.",
        "hint": "$x^2 \\to \\frac{x^3}{3}$ and $x \\to \\frac{x^2}{2}$, giving $\\frac{x^3}{3} + \\frac{x^2}{2}$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-3",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "To evaluate a definite integral, the Fundamental Theorem says: find an antiderivative $F$, then subtract its values at the endpoints, $F(b) - F(a)$. For polynomials, $F$ comes straight from the reverse power rule."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_0^2 (2x + 1)\\,dx = \\big[x^2 + x\\big]_0^2 = (4 + 2) - 0 = 6",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Here $F(x) = x^2 + x$ is an antiderivative of $2x + 1$, and evaluating it from 0 to 2 gives 6."
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-4",
      "type": "numeric",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Your turn. Use the antiderivative $F(x) = x^2 + x$ to evaluate this integral as $F(3) - F(0)$."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_0^3 (2x + 1)\\,dx",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "2*x + 1",
          "domain": [0, 4],
          "yDomain": [0, 9],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 3,
          "static": true
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": { "type": "numeric", "value": 12, "tolerance": 0.1 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Exactly — $F(3) - F(0) = (9 + 3) - 0 = 12$.",
        "incorrect": "Evaluate $x^2 + x$ at 3 and at 0, then subtract.",
        "hint": "$F(3) - F(0) = (9 + 3) - 0 = 12$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-5",
      "type": "slider_graph",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "The shaded region is the area under $f(x) = x + 1$ from 0 to $t$. Its antiderivative is $F(x) = \\frac{1}{2}x^2 + x$. Find the value of $t$ for which this area equals 4, then drag the slider there."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_0^t (x + 1)\\,dx = 4",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "x + 1",
          "domain": [0, 4],
          "yDomain": [0, 5],
          "sliderLabel": "t",
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showSecant": false,
          "showValue": false,
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "showAreaValue": false,
          "sliderMin": 0,
          "sliderMax": 4,
          "sliderStep": 0.5,
          "initialSlider": 0
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": {
          "type": "slider",
          "value": 2,
          "tolerance": 0.2
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Nice — $\\frac{1}{2}t^2 + t = 4$ gives $t^2 + 2t - 8 = 0$, so $(t - 2)(t + 4) = 0$ and $t = 2$.",
        "incorrect": "Set $\\frac{1}{2}t^2 + t = 4$ and solve for $t$, then drag the slider there.",
        "hint": "$\\frac{1}{2}t^2 + t = 4 \\to t^2 + 2t - 8 = 0 \\to (t - 2)(t + 4) = 0 \\to t = 2$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-6",
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Reverse the power rule with coefficients. Which is an antiderivative of $f(x) = 6x^2 + 2x$?"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "6*x^2 + 2*x",
          "domain": [0, 2],
          "yDomain": [0, 28],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 1,
          "static": true
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": {
          "type": "multiple_choice",
          "options": [
            "$2x^3 + x^2$",
            "$6x^3 + 2x^2$",
            "$12x + 2$",
            "$3x^3 + x^2$"
          ],
          "correctIndex": 0
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — $6x^2 \\to 6 \\cdot \\frac{x^3}{3} = 2x^3$ and $2x \\to 2 \\cdot \\frac{x^2}{2} = x^2$. Check by differentiating: $\\frac{d}{dx}(2x^3 + x^2) = 6x^2 + 2x$.",
        "incorrect": "Integrate each term: raise the exponent and divide, keeping the coefficients.",
        "hint": "$6x^2 \\to 2x^3$ and $2x \\to x^2$, giving $2x^3 + x^2$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-7",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "You can now run calculus in both directions on any polynomial: differentiate term by term with the power rule, or integrate term by term with the reverse power rule — and with the Fundamental Theorem, turn those antiderivatives into exact areas."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Derivatives, integrals, and the theorem that unites them — that's the heart of calculus. Nice work making it through!"
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    }
  ],
  "practiceBank": [
    {
      "id": "ip-practice-1",
      "type": "numeric",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Use $F(x) = x^2 + x$ to evaluate the integral of $2x + 1$ from 0 to 2."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_0^2 (2x + 1)\\,dx",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "2*x + 1",
          "domain": [0, 3],
          "yDomain": [0, 7],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 2,
          "static": true
        },
        "answer": { "type": "numeric", "value": 6, "tolerance": 0.1 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Yes — $(2^2 + 2) - 0 = 6$.",
        "incorrect": "Evaluate $x^2 + x$ at 2 and 0, then subtract.",
        "hint": "$(4 + 2) - 0 = 6$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-practice-2",
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Which is an antiderivative of $f(x) = x^3 + x$?"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "x^3 + x",
          "domain": [0, 2],
          "yDomain": [0, 10],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 1,
          "static": true
        },
        "answer": {
          "type": "multiple_choice",
          "options": [
            "$\\frac{x^4}{4} + \\frac{x^2}{2}$",
            "$x^4 + x^2$",
            "$3x^2 + 1$",
            "$\\frac{x^4}{4} + x^2$"
          ],
          "correctIndex": 0
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — $x^3 \\to \\frac{x^4}{4}$ and $x \\to \\frac{x^2}{2}$.",
        "incorrect": "Add 1 to each exponent and divide by the new exponent.",
        "hint": "$\\frac{x^4}{4} + \\frac{x^2}{2}$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-practice-3",
      "type": "numeric",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Evaluate the integral of $4x^3 + 2x$ from 0 to 1. (An antiderivative is $x^4 + x^2$.)"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_0^1 (4x^3 + 2x)\\,dx",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "4*x^3 + 2*x",
          "domain": [0, 1.5],
          "yDomain": [0, 17],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 1,
          "static": true
        },
        "answer": { "type": "numeric", "value": 2, "tolerance": 0.1 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Yes — $(1 + 1) - 0 = 2$.",
        "incorrect": "Evaluate $x^4 + x^2$ at 1 and 0, then subtract.",
        "hint": "$(1 + 1) - 0 = 2$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-practice-4",
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Which is an antiderivative of $f(x) = 2x + 3$?"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "2*x + 3",
          "domain": [0, 3],
          "yDomain": [0, 9],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 2,
          "static": true
        },
        "answer": {
          "type": "multiple_choice",
          "options": [
            "$x^2 + 3x$",
            "$2x^2 + 3x$",
            "$x^2 + 3$",
            "$2$"
          ],
          "correctIndex": 0
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — $2x \\to x^2$ and $3 \\to 3x$.",
        "incorrect": "Integrate each term separately with the reverse power rule, then combine.",
        "hint": "$x^2 + 3x$."
      }
    }
  ]
}
